\begin_body

\begin_layout Title
Wavelet scattering on the Shepard pitch spiral
\end_layout

\begin_layout Author
18 mai 2015
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Introduction
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection*
On the two dimensions of musical pitch
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Behind the circularity of the musical scale, lies a simple fact: when raising
 a harmonic note by exactly one octave, even-numbered partials seem unchanged,
 whereas odd-numbered partials disappear.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Although frequency is expressed in Hertz as a rectilinear quantity, there
 are two natural degrees of freedom for pitch.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Definition of pitch chroma and pitch height.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Locality relations between pure tones is better expressed in a spiral (Shepard)
 than on a line.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection*
Problem
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
The spiral model is well-known in music theory.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
However, existing methods in audio classification do not fully take advantage
 from its richness: they either picture pitch on a line (MFCC) or on a circle
 (chroma features).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection*
Contributions
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
We present a new representation of sounds that is derived from the Shepard
 spiral.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
We present a new representation of sounds that disentangles variations in
 pitch chroma and pitch height by taking pitch circularity into account.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection*
Shepard tones
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A Shepard tone is a sum of sine waves which are one octave apart:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
x(t)=\sum_{k=0}^{K-1}\sin(2\pi2^{k}f_{0}t)
\]

\end_inset

Shepard tones do not have a specifitch pitch height ; instead, they are
 entirely determined by their pitch chroma.
 Moreover, Shepard tones are self-similar: 
\begin_inset Formula $x(2t)\approx x(t)$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection*
Shepard pitch spiral
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\log_{2}\lambda_{1}=\lfloor\log_{2}\lambda_{1}\rfloor+\lbrace\log_{2}\lambda_{1}\rbrace
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The integer part 
\begin_inset Formula $\lfloor\log_{2}\lambda_{1}\rfloor$
\end_inset

 is related to pitch height, whereas the fractional part 
\begin_inset Formula $\{\log_{2}\lambda_{1}\}$
\end_inset

 is related to pitch chroma.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection*
Spiral wavelet
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\Psi_{\lambda_{2}}(t,\lambda_{1})=\psi_{\alpha}(t)\times\psi_{\beta}(\log_{2}\lambda_{1})\times\psi_{\gamma}(\lfloor\log_{2}\lambda_{1}\rfloor)
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
x_{2}(t,\lambda_{1},\lambda_{2})=\vert x_{1}\ast\Psi_{\lambda_{2}}\vert(t,\lambda_{1})
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection*
Shepard-Risset glissando
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
x_{\tau}(t)=x\left(\tau(t)\right)
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\tau=\dfrac{T_{\mathrm{chroma}}}{\log2}2^{t/T_{\mathrm{chroma}}}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $T_{\mathrm{chroma}}$
\end_inset

 is the duration of a full octave rise in pitch chroma.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The Shepard-Risset glissando yields a simple particular case of a result
 proven by Joakim And√©n on joint time-frequency characterization of chirps:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
x_{2,\tau}(t,\lambda_{1},\lambda_{2})\propto\widehat{\psi}\left(-\dfrac{\beta\log2}{\alpha T_{\mathrm{chroma}}}\right)
\]

\end_inset

In other words, 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{2}$
\end_inset

 is maximal when the slope 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha/\beta$
\end_inset

 is equal to 
\begin_inset Formula $\log2/T_{\mathrm{chroma}}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection*
Shepard pagoda
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
x_{g}(t)=\sum_{k=1}^{K}2^{k}g\left(\dfrac{t}{T_{\mathrm{height}}}-k\right)\sin(2\pi2^{k}f_{0}t)
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $T_{\mathrm{height}}$
\end_inset

 is the duration of a full octave rise in pitch height.
 
\begin_inset Formula $g$
\end_inset

 is a zero-centered bump function ; we have chosen a standard Gaussian in
 our experiments.
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
x_{2,g}(t,\lambda_{1},\lambda_{2})\propto g\left(\dfrac{T_{\text{\mathrm{height}}}+\frac{\gamma}{\beta}}{\alpha T_{\mathrm{height}}}\right)
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_body
